0–1279","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1260–1290":"1260–1290","1203–1230":"1203–1230","–Female":"Overleden","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1203":"1203","1236":"1236","1279":"1279","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shocklache, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shocklach, Cheshire, England":"Shocklach, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1230–1279":"1230–1279","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1260–1290":"1260–1290","1203–1230":"1203–1230","–Female":"Deceased","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1203":"1203","1236":"1236","1279":"1279","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shocklache, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shocklach, Cheshire, England":"Shocklach, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Patric","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the personal name <i>Patrice</i>, Latin <i>Patricius</i> (see   Patrick  ). This surname is also found in the West Indies and Martinique.","Altered form of French   Patry  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Patrick","meanings":["Irish, Scottish, and English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French, Middle English, and Older Scots personal name <i>Patrick</i> (Old Irish <i>Patraicc</i>), derived from Latin <i>Patricius</i> ‘son of a noble father, member of the patrician class’. This was the name of a Christian saint, a 5th-century Romano-Briton who became the apostle and patron saint of Ireland, and it was largely as a result of his fame that the personal name was so popular from the Middle Ages onward. In Ireland the surname is usually Scottish in origin, from Scottish settlers in Ulster in the 17th century. See also   Peden   and   McPadden  , derived from pet forms of Old Irish <i>Patraicc</i>.","Scottish and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Scottish and Irish Gaelic <b>Mac Phádraig</b> ‘son of Patrick’.","English: variant of   Partridge  ."]},{"name":"Patry","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Jean-Guy, Pierre, Benoit, Gaston, Gisele, Jean-Pierre, Julien, Luc, Lucien, Marcel, Michel.","French: from a vernacular form of the personal name   Patrice   (see   Patrick  ). Compare   Patrie  .","English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Patry</i>, a pet form of   Patrick   and (in Scotland)   Peter  . Compare Scottish   Petrie  , of which this was sometimes a variant. This name was formerly widespread, especially in western England and northeast Scotland, but is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Patric was born in 1230, in Cheshire, England as the son of Sir Robert Griffin Patrick -Lord of Castle Shokelach and Beatrix. He married Beatrice Malpas in 1258, in 